 The probability of getting exactly k heads in m flips of an unfair coin is given by the binomial distribution:

{eq}\begin{align}

P(X=k)&=\left(\begin{array}{c}m\\k\end{array}\right) p^k (1-p)^{m-k}

\end{align}

{/eq}

Here, {eq}p{/eq} is the probability of getting heads in one flip. Since it is given that it is twice as likely to come up heads, so we have,

{eq}\begin{align}

p&=2(1-p)\\2p&=2-p\\3p&=2\\p&=2/3\\(1-p)&=1/3

\end{align}

{/eq}

As per the question, the probability of getting three heads in 8 flips is,

{eq}\begin{align}

P(8,H)=\left(\begin{array}{c}8\\3\end{array}\right)\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^3\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^5

\end{align}

{/eq}

And the probability of getting two heads in 8 flips is,

{eq}\begin{align}

P(8,HH)=\left(\begin{array}{c}8\\2\end{array}\right)\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^6

\end{align}

{/eq}

Now the ratio of the two probabilities is given by,

{eq}\begin{align}

\frac{P(8,H)}{P(8,HH)}&=\frac{\left(\begin{array}{c}8\\3\end{array}\right)\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^3\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^5}{\left(\begin{array}{c}8\\2\end{array}\right)\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^6}\\

&=\frac{\frac{8!}{3!5!}}{\frac{8!}{2!6!}}\frac{\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^3\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^5}{\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^6}\\

&=\frac{6}{1}\times \frac{3}{1}\\

&=18

\end{align}

{/eq}

And so the chances of getting exactly 3 heads is 18 times more probable than to get exactly 2 heads.
